"meanings":["Norman, English:  See  Dawnay  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dawnay","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from one of the many places in northern France named from an alder grove (Old French  <i>aulnai</i>,  <i>aulnoi</i>, latinized as  <i>alnetum</i>), such as Annay (Pas-de-Calais), Aulnay (Aube, Marne, Calvados), Aulnois (Aisne), and Aunay (Calvados, Eure-et-Loire, Seine-et-Oise). With fused preposition, Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunai</i> became  <i>Dawnay</i>,  <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable)  <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article.  See also  Dando  , from Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which  <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Dawney was born in 1398, in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John D’Aunay, was 34 and his mother, Ellen De Barden, was 28. He married MARGARET Joan Lound about 1414. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 12 July 1425, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1398–12 Jul 1425":"1398–12. juuli 1425","1398–1425":"1398–1425","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1402–Female":"1402–Surnud","1404–1460":"1404–1460","1400–1454":"1400–1454","1424–1493":"1424–1493","1425–1475":"1425–1475","1364–1417":"1364–1417","1370–1440":"1370–1440","12 Jul 1425":"12. juuli 1425","1440":"1440","1493":"1493","1460":"1460","ABT 1414":"umbes 1414","1370":"1370","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","1424":"1424","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1454":"1454","1398":"1398","13 July 1417":"13. juuli 1417","1475":"1475","1397":"1397","1364":"1364","1417":"1417","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Molesden, Northumberland, England":"Molesden, Northumberland, England","Cowick, Yorks